		<paragraph height="0" width="605" y="+16" x="12"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT SIZE="2"></FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<field id="1" group="1" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="false">A.  Pictures have more impact than words.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="2" group="2" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">B.  If unpleasant images are shown on television, people may take action.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="3" group="3" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">C.  Important news events must not be 'censored' for the public, even if the images are unpleasant.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="4" group="4" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">D.  If you find the images upsetting, you can turn the television off.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="5" group="5" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="false">E.  Some political systems work better when people know exactly what is happening in the world.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="6" group="6" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">F.  Young people should not be sheltered from the unpleasant realities of the world.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="7" group="7" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">A.  Victims of violence may not want to be shown on television.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="8" group="8" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="false">B.  Television news reports often trivialise tragic events by turning them into entertainment.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="9" group="9" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">C.  Viewers are not always given enough warning before disturbing images are shown.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="10" group="10" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="false">D.  Viewers want to be entertained, not distressed, when they watch television.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="11" group="11" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">E.  Children may be traumatised by disturbing images.</answer>
		</field>
		<field id="12" group="12" type="i:target" mode="0">
			<answer correct="true">F.  Too much exposure to disturbing images may accustom us to them, so we no longer react.</answer>
		</field>
